#: ../../../topics/request-response.rst:64
msgid ""
"the request cookies. These can be sent in two forms.  1. Using a dict::      "
"request_with_cookies = Request(url=\"http://www.example."
"com\",                                    cookies={'currency': 'USD', "
"'country': 'UY'}) 2. Using a list of dicts::      request_with_cookies = "
"Request(url=\"http://www.example.com\",                                    "
"cookies=[{'name': 'currency',                                             "
"'value': 'USD',                                             'domain': "
"'example.com',                                             'path': '/"
"currency'}])  The latter form allows for customizing the ``domain`` and "
"``path`` attributes of the cookie. This is only useful if the cookies are "
"saved for later requests.  When some site returns cookies (in a response) "
"those are stored in the cookies for that domain and will be sent again in "
"future requests. That's the typical behaviour of any regular web browser. "
"However, if, for some reason, you want to avoid merging with existing "
"cookies you can instruct Scrapy to do so by setting the "
"``dont_merge_cookies`` key in the :attr:`Request.meta`.  Example of request "
"without merging cookies::      request_with_cookies = Request(url=\"http://"
"www.example.com\",                                    cookies={'currency': "
"'USD', 'country': 'UY'},                                    "
"meta={'dont_merge_cookies': True})  For more info see :ref:`cookies-mw`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/request-response.rst:64
